== Legacy ==
Carter was inducted as part of the Original [[Carter Family]] in the [[Country Music Hall of Fame]] in 1970, along with [[Bill Monroe]].
<ref name="CMHF">{{cite web|last=Wolfe|first=Charles|title=Carter Family|publisher=Country Music Hall of Fame & Museum|url=http://www.countrymusichalloffame.org/full-list-of-inductees/view/carter-family|accessdate=February 17, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807062544/http://countrymusichalloffame.org/full-list-of-inductees/view/carter-family|archivedate=August 7, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 1993, her image appeared on a U.S. postage stamp honoring the Carter Family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1993-09-12/entertainment/9309080581_1_american-music-series-customer-affixed-stamps-first-day-cancellations|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325202522/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1993-09-12/entertainment/9309080581_1_american-music-series-customer-affixed-stamps-first-day-cancellations|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 25, 2017|title='Legends' Series Salutes Country-western Stars|website=Sun-Sentinel|access-date=2016-05-04}}</ref> In 2001 she was inducted into the [[International Bluegrass Music Hall of Honor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bluegrassmuseum.org/sara-carter/|title=Sara Carter|website=International Bluegrass Music Museum|access-date=2016-05-04}}</ref>

On her 2008 album ''[[All I Intended to Be]]'', [[Emmylou Harris]] includes the song "How She Could Sing the Wildwood Flower", co-written with [[Kate and Anna McGarrigle]] about the relationship between Sara and A.P., inspired by a documentary that the three of them saw on television.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}

==Death==
[[File:Grave of Sara Carter Bayes and children at Mount Vernon United Methodist Church at Maces Springs, Virginia now Hiltons, Virginia.jpg|thumb|right|Grave of Sara Carter Bayes and children at [[Mount Vernon United Methodist Church]] at [[Hiltons, Virginia]]]]
Sara Carter died in [[Lodi, California]], aged 80,<ref>{{Cite news |date=1979-01-09 |title=Sara Carter Bayes obit-Lodi 1979 |pages=28 |work=The San Francisco Examiner |url=https://www.newspapers.com/article/the-san-francisco-examiner-sara-carter-b/36095944/ |access-date=2023-12-12}}</ref> and is interred in the Mt. Vernon United Methodist Church graveyard in [[Hiltons, Virginia]]. The [[A. P. and Sara Carter House]], [[A. P. Carter Homeplace]], [[A. P. Carter Store]], [[Maybelle and Ezra Carter House]], and [[Mt. Vernon Methodist Church]] are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] as components of the Carter Family Thematic Resource.<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref><ref>{{NRHP url|id=64000880|title=Carter family profile}}, pdfhost.focus.nps.gov (PDF); accessed November 14, 2015.</ref>

